ABUJA  – Executive Director/CEO, National Film and Video Censors Board (NFVCB), Alhaji Adedayo Thomas has hinted that the board received and censored a total of 382 movies pro­duced by the Nigerian film industry in the last quarter of 2021. He declared this in a state­ment made available to news­men in Abuja by his media aide, Joshua Olumu. The statement reads: “The figure was made available by the Department of Film Cen­sorship and Classification of the board in its fourth-quarter report for the year, which cap­tured all films submitted to the board from across the country. 2023: North East, North Central Legislators Back Yahaya Bello BREAKING: Sanwo-Olu Reinstates Suspended LASU Registrar, Amuni “The report is for onward submission to the relevant Federal Government author­ity for the compilation of the nation’s Gross Domestic Product (GDP) for the fourth quarter (GDP) Q3, 2021. “We are happy that the industry is picking up again, having survived the harsh im­pact of the COVID pandemic on every sector of our econ­omy, including the creative sector and the motion picture industry in particular. “We introduced virtual censorship platforms to keep the industry running so as not to jeopardise the business interest of stakeholders, and that has become an integral part of our operations,” the statement added.